{"author":{"id":"15a88cc68503e42ab24006333304090e606ec65782bc59288f3c1c3e49bb4654"},"ops":[{"type":6,"timestamp":1783001692,"nonce":"WAVD0VbFLzHynGgwMLeZFKXD1Gc=","metadata":{"github-id":"UCE_lAHOOEv6_s8AAAABHNOlnM7K0UwF"},"target":"b55560ba2988616b55c0b31568c877b3b62eadf501a12fd7105dcfafcf33b5dd","message":"At the moment the entirety of `gwr-engine` is designed to be single threaded and therefore `Task`s are not thread safe and cannot be moved between CPU threads.\n\nWe should be able to run large scale simulations using multiple threads/CPUs each running separate engines. This will only be efficient when there is minimal communication between the engines. That means it makes most sense to split a simulation of a large scale model in a way that reflects a real physical system along lines where there is minimal communication/synchronisation.\n\nFor example, having the ability to model two large ASICs connected by an control link that allows for synchronisation and data sharing:\n```\n{\n  let engine_0 = Engine::new();\n  let engine_1 = Engine::new();\n  let (tx_0, rx_0) = MultiEngineChannel::new();\n  let (tx_1, rx_1) = MultiEngineChannel::new();\n\n  let handles = [\n    thread::spawn(|| {\n        build_cpu_model(\u0026engine_0, tx_0, rx_1);\n        engine_0.run()?;\n    }),\n    thread::spawn(|| {\n        build_cpu_model(\u0026engine_1, tx_0, rx_1);\n        engine_1.run()?;\n    })\n  ];\n\n  for handle in handles.into_iter() {\n    handle.join();\n  }\n}\n```\n\nAnd the `MultiEngineChannel` would each CPU model to be able to synchronise with the other one and have time advance to the highest of the two engine times at the point of synchronisation.\n\nWe also need to consider how to move data between the two engines. This would require types to be `Send`.\n\nThe engines themselves would be doing something like:\n```\n  while !done {\n    let done = do_work().await;\n    let time = max(time_now, sync_with_other_engine());\n    clock.advance_to(time);\n  }\n```"